            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Invalid: this is a GCC LTO bug. Sorry for wasting your time!\nHere's our `rpmbuild` fix: https://github.com/Xpra-org/xpra/commit/b351c1c2ca16c1569aadeb229eb38def8e8d1994\nBelow is the AI diagnosis which I have followed for hours - and it all looks reasonable to get here.\nI've also verified that disabling lto results in usable builds again with GCC 16.\n\n---\n\nSame correct Nodes.c (948 gotos):\n```\n┌─────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────┐\n│ gcc-16 build of Nodes.c │ resulting Nodes.so codegen │\n├─────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────┤\n│ -O2 (no LTO)            │ correct (goto emitted)     │\n├─────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────┤\n│ -O2 -flto=auto          │ broken (goto dropped)      │\n└─────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────┘\n```\nGCC-16's LTO miscompiles Cython's `Nodes.c`, so the compiled `Nodes.so` omits the `put_goto` call for if/else.\nThis explains everything: the Cython maintainer can't reproduce (not their code), pure-Python Cython is fine (no compilation), all if/else break uniformly, and every rpm rebuild stays broken because Fedora's RPM_OPT_FLAGS enables LTO.\n\nFWIW: I've been using LTO with our cython builds for years without noticing any issues!\n\nFedora 44\ngcc (GCC) 16.1.1 20260515 (Red Hat 16.1.1-2)",
