            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> your GCC and build flags rather than a general problem\n\nThis is stock Fedora 44.\n\n---\n`-fno-ipa-icf` is the \"fix\".\n\nFWIW: Claude narrowed right down to `GCC-16 IPA-ICF`: _under -flto, folds `__Pyx_PyObject_CompareIntIntNe` into `__Pyx_PyObject_CompareIntIntEq`_\nFrom the `-fdump-ipa-icf-details dump`: optimized: Semantic equality hit: `__Pyx_PyObject_CompareIntIntNe` -> `__Pyx_PyObject_CompareIntIntEq` The two functions are byte-identical except a conditional branch goes to the opposite return label\n(`__pyx_return_true=Py_RETURN_TRUE`, `__pyx_return_false=Py_RETURN_FALSE`.)\nAfter folding, `!=` returns the `==` result; Cython's `IfStatNode` computes `is_last = (i == last)`, that flips, so the guarded `put_goto` is skipped and the else runs unconditionally. Looks like an ICF block-equivalence bug treating the two `Py_RETURN_TRUE`/`FALSE` successor blocks as interchangeable.\n\nI don't have access to gcc's bugzilla so I can't file it.",
